The TemplateRenderer in bamboo-api only renders templates into Strings, which it returns.  This means that the output of every template it renders gets buffered twice, firstly in the StringWriter it writes to, and then in the String that the StringWriter creates when the toString() method is called.  If the user of the TemplateRenderer has a writer (for example, the HttpServletResponse), this buffering is totally unnecessary and will inhibit performance and cause each request to use more memory.  It would be much better if a method was added to TemplateRenderer that accepted a Writer for it to write to, for example:

{code:java}
void renderPage(String path, Map params, Writer writer) throws IOException;
{code}

Bamboo.sh starts bamboo with
{{RUN_CMD="java -Xms256m -Xmx512m -XX:MaxPermSize=256m}}
accoding to our [installation documentation | http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Bamboo+Installation+Guide] setting JAVA_HOME points bamboo to the JDK of choice.

This is not the case as the system's java JDK is used as defined in {code}$ whereis java{code}

We should clarify this to avoid confusion. Possibly JAVA_HOME can be checked in used if defined in bamboo.sh.

